<DOC><DOCNO> AP880804-0139 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-04-88 2205EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u i AM-Guatemala     08-04 0355</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Guatemala,0364</SECOND><HEAD>Three Detained in Reported Coup Plot</HEAD><BYLINE>By ALFONSO ANZUETO</BYLINE><BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE><DATELINE>GUATEMALA CITY (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   President Vinicio Cerezo on Thursday saidthree civilians were arrested in connection with a plot todestabilize his government.   In a brief statement, Cerezo said the three tried to involvegovernment officials in a plot ``to destabilize the democraticsystem'' but gave no further details.   The president identified the three as Guillermo Florian Crorado,40; Alejandro Guzman Roman, 60; and Jose Martin Recinos de Zepeda,43.   Cerezo said the men were detained in Guatemala City, thecapital, and that the case was being referred to judicial courts.He did not say what charges would be brought against them.   Cerezo also announced that he would not attend the inaugurationof Ecuadoran President-elect Rodrigo Borja in Quito on Wednesday.He cited pressing matters of economic policy for his decision toremain in Guatemala.   Earlier Thursday, army spokesman Col. Luis Arturo IsaacsRodriguez denied there had been any coup plot against the president.   Rodriguez said in a telephone interview that Cerezo met withDefense Minister Gen. Hector Alejandro Gramajo Morales on Thursdaybut did not discuss any efforts to overthrow the government.   The newspaper La Hora reported Thursday a coup attempt had beenbroken up by the government on July 30. It said three people werearrested in connection with the plot, but did not cite any sourcesfor the report.   Rumors have circulated in the capital that the three civiliansapproached several military officers to solicit their help inoverthrowing the government. Reports that the three belong to theopposition right-ring National Liberation Movement could not beindependently confirmed.   Army forces loyal to Cerezo's government quashed a coup attempton May 11 led by dissident officers in the divided military. Fivecivilians and six military officers were charged in the attempt butwere later freed under an amnesty declared by the Congress.   Cerezo, a lawyer and leader of the Christian Democratic Party,was elected to a five-year term in November 1985. It was the firstelection in 16 years in which the military did not field acandidate.</TEXT></DOC>